abstract: ASBURY PARK, N.J., Aug. 4.--The severest storm of the season visited this place to-day. The streets were flooded, and the many swollen strearns rushing into Wesley Lake, broke down the gates of the new dam, built last Winter at great expense, and the immense body of water rushed into the ocean. The dam gates are about 100 yards from the sea, and this the third time within two years that this accident has happened.

abstract: CHICAGO, Aug. 11.--Alvin Dexterevert, 60 years old, committed suicide this morning by taking laudanum. The act is said to have been caused by a refusal of admission to the house of his sister-inlaw. An examination of his body disclosed a bullet-hole under the left breast, and a scar on the back where the ball had passed out. The wounds, which are partially healed, are thought to be two days' old.

abstract: NEWPORT, Aug. 21.--It is 100 years ago. Thames-street presents a gala appearance. Groups of officers with magnificent white uniforms and costly side-arms burnished in gold and precious stones move up the street. abstract: ATLANTA, Ga., Aug. 27.--On Wednesday night, near Cochran, Ga., four young white men disguised themselves, went to a negro cabin, broke down the door, and commenced firing into it. The occupant, John Brown, seized his double-barreled gun, which was loaded with buckshot, and fired both barrels, killing two brothers named Dykes. The tops of their heads were blown off. The negro made his escape. The Coroner's jury rendered a verdict of justifiable homicide.

abstract: Yesterday's storm struck Coney Island at a few minutes before 6 o'clock, when all the beaches were crowded. Not less than 50,0000 visitors were on the island. abstract: The quantity of peaches which arrived from Delaware and Maryland last week was not as great as during the previous week, nor as great as was generally looked for.
